{"id":"1609.05221","submitter":"Thorsten Wissmann","authors":"Danny Rorabaugh, Claude Tardif and David Wehlau","title":"Logical compactness and constraint satisfaction problems","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Logical Methods in Computer Science, Volume 13, Issue 1 (January\n  23, 2017) lmcs:2663","doi":"10.23638/LMCS-13(1:1)2017","report-no":null,"categories":"math.LO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate a correspondence between the complexity hierarchy of\nconstraint satisfaction problems and a hierarchy of logical compactness\nhypotheses for finite relational structures. It seems that the harder a\nconstraint satisfaction problem is, the stronger the corresponding compactness\nhypothesis is. At the top level, the NP-complete constraint satisfaction\nproblems correspond to compactness hypotheses that are equivalent to the\nultrafilter axiom in all the cases we have investigated. At the bottom level,\nthe simplest constraint satisfaction problems correspond to compactness\nhypotheses that are readily provable from the axioms of Zermelo and Fraenkel.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 16 Sep 2016 20:17:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 14 Dec 2016 16:19:32 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 22 Dec 2016 18:17:05 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 18 Jan 2017 16:53:07 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Fri, 20 Jan 2017 18:59:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-14"}
{"id":"1609.05222","submitter":"Samir Mathur","authors":"Samir D. Mathur","title":"What prevents gravitational collapse in string theory?","comments":"6 pages (Essay awarded an honorable mention in the Gravity Research\n  Foundation 2016 essay competition.)","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1142/S0218271816440181","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is conventionally believed that if a ball of matter of mass $M$ has a\nradius close to $2GM$ then it must collapse to a black hole. But string theory\nmicrostates (fuzzballs) have no horizon or singularity, and they do {\\it not}\ncollapse. We consider two simple examples from classical gravity to illustrate\nhow this violation of our intuition happens. In each case the `matter' arises\nfrom an extra compact dimension, but the topology of this extra dimension is\nnot trivial. The pressure and density of this matter diverge at various points,\nbut this is only an artifact of dimensional reduction; thus we bypass results\nlike Buchadahl's theorem. Such microstates give the entropy of black holes, so\nthese topologically nontrivial constructions dominate the state space of\nquantum gravity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 16 Sep 2016 20:26:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-11-15"}
